queryItem.name: LiabilityId
queryItem.description: This is NULLable because a LiabilityId may not be assigned yet when a transaction first hits the ledger.

shortcut.name: Liabilities (JE)
shortcut.description: {\rtf1\ansi\deff0{\fonttbl{\f0\fnil\fcharset0 MS Shell Dlg 2;}} \viewkind4\uc1\pard\lang1033\f0\fs17 As payroll transactions come in, they are assigned a liability. \par \par For taxes, these are usually broken down by TaxCodes. So we will aggregate all tax amounts for a single payroll run, break it up by TaxCodes, and then assign a Liability for each Tax Code.\par \par The word 'Liability' here sounds like the accrual-based accounting term, but in reality these "Liabilities" are cash-basis. They are only created when we know how much cash we need to pay out, so they represent the cash payment, not the accrual.\par }

querySubject.name: LiabilityCollections
querySubject.description:
Once a Liability is created, we need to collect the funds to satisfy this Liability. Usually we aggregate multiple Liabilities into a single Collection in order to minimize bank transactions, so that we can minimize bank fees.
So, many Liabilities go into a single Collection.

querySubject.name: TaxAmounts
querySubject.description: This is the detail table to TaxPayrolls. This contains the rows for the individual tax transactions that are generated for a payroll that comes in.

querySubject.name: TaxCodes
querySubject.description:
The reason why we don't have TaxCodes in this table is that the mapping between TaxId and TaxCode is very complicated and varies over time. UTE does not really have the UltiPro Tax Code in it, but when they send us transactions (which are stored in the TaxAmounts table), they include the Ultipro Tax Code in there as a reference. However, in the API that sends us the data for this table, there is no Ultipro Tax Code included.
However, why don't we have the UTE Tax Code in this table either?

querySubject.name: TaxPayrolls
querySubject.description:
When an Ultipro payroll comes into UTE, we create transactions for each tax inside that payroll, and these tax transactions eventually become liabilities.
This is the header table for such a payroll that comes in, which results in a single Liability being created for all the Taxes that need to be paid for that payroll.
The TaxAmounts table is the child or detail table for this table.

querySubject.name: Liabilities
querySubject.description: {\rtf1\ansi\deff0{\fonttbl{\f0\fnil\fcharset0 MS Shell Dlg 2;}} \viewkind4\uc1\pard\lang1033\f0\fs17 As payroll transactions come in, they are assigned a liability. \par \par For taxes, these are usually broken down by TaxCodes. So we will aggregate all tax amounts for a single payroll run, break it up by TaxCodes, and then assign a Liability for each Tax Code.\par \par The word 'Liability' here sounds like the accrual-based accounting term, but in reality these "Liabilities" are cash-basis. They are only created when we know how much cash we need to pay out, so they represent the cash payment, not the accrual.\par }

querySubject.name: Tax Payrolls
querySubject.description:
When an Ultipro payroll comes into UTE, we create transactions for each tax inside that payroll, and these tax transactions eventually become liabilities.
This is the header table for such a payroll that comes in, which results in a single Liability being created for all the Taxes that need to be paid for that payroll.
The TaxAmounts table is the child or detail table for this table.
